h Unit-level concerns. Thread safety and reliability under actual concurrent load are Integration and System concerns respectively.\n\nNow reconsidering behavior 5, which is the most critical one. The 10,000 entries per second requirement could fail in several ways: an O(n²) algorithm would cause slowdown and falling behind (caught by Integration load testing), a fixed-size queue could overflow and drop entries (Integration with queue monitoring), memory exhaustion could occur under sustained load (Integration with memory checks or System with real pressure), and lock contention could degrade performance under concurrent access (Integration with concurrent scenarios or System-level testing). The distribution should heavily weight Integration since most realistic failures manifest under load conditions rather than in isolated unit tests.\n\nFor behavior 5:\n- Unit: 0.10\n- Integration: 0.70\n- System: 0.20\n\nThe System portion covers network I/O bottlenecks and garbage collection pauses, which are harder to simulate at Integration level. Network failures require actual network conditions, while GC behavior depends on runtime specifics. Integration testing handles the algorithmic and queue-based failures effectively, so the bulk of effort goes there.\n\nThe real question is how logs enter the system from multiple microservices. If they arrive via HTTP or message queues, network I/O becomes critical and System testing is necessary. If it's a local library API, Integration suffices. Since the problem doesn't specify but microservices typically communicate over the network, I should assume System-level testing is needed for production confidence, though Integration testing with synthetic load can catch most real failures.\n\nFor behavior 5, the core failure to detect is whether the system actually processes 10,000 entries per second without dropping data. I can construct this test at Integration level by programmatically generating 10,000 entries, feeding them through t