avior statement doesn't mention concurrency or completeness—it just says logs \"are grouped together\". So Unit is the correct minimum level. The real failure here is \"logs with the same trace ID are not grouped together\", and a Unit test verifying grouping logic would catch this. A test feeding logs with matching and distinct trace IDs would verify the grouping is correct, catching the failure in production.\n\nHowever, if the real failure is \"under concurrent load, some logs are lost and not grouped\", then a Unit test wouldn't catch this—Integration or higher testing would be needed. But the behavior statement aligns more with the former interpretation, so Unit is correct.\n\nFinal assignment for behavior 1: Unit 0.70, Integration 0.25, System 0.05.\n\n---\n\nFor behavior 2:\n\n\"The timeline view orders entries by timestamp, correctly handling clock skew of up to 500ms between services.\"\n\nThe behavior requires:\n1. Ordering entries by timestamp\n2. Handling clock skew of up to 500ms\n\nReal failures would be ordering broken or clock skew > 500ms not handled. These can be caught at Unit level with test data including various timestamp scenarios and clock skew. However, ordering could fail under concurrent load from multiple services (Integration) or when real clock drift > 500ms occurs (System), but these are less likely given the behavior statement.\n\nFinal assignment for behavior 2: Unit 0.75, Integration 0.15, System 0.10.\n\n---\n\nFor behavior 3:\n\n\"A latency spike (p99 above 3x the baseline) is detected and flagged in the anomaly report.\"\n\nReal failures include detection logic being broken, baseline calculation being wrong, or detection not working at all. These are Unit-level concerns—I can test the detection algorithm with mock data showing latency spikes and verify it flags them correctly. However, detection could fail under real production load (Integration) or with actual latency patterns (System), but the behavior statement focuses on the 